lan' Land New 2020 Release Dates, 'Jungle Cruise' Delayed a Year|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404000547/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/black-widow-mulan-nab-new-release-dates-jungle-cruise-delayed-a-year-1286854|archive-date=April 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"AprilAnime\">{{cite web |title=2020 Detective Conan, Crayon Shin-chan Films Delayed |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-04-03/2020-detective-conan-crayon-shin-chan-films-delayed/.158262 |website=[[Anime News Network]] |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406000617/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-04-03/2020-detective-conan-crayon-shin-chan-films-delayed/.158262 |archive-date=April 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Doremon2\">{{cite web |title=Doraemon: Nobita no Shin Kyory\u016b Film Rescheduled for August 7, Stand By Me Doraemon 2 Film Delayed |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-03-19/doraemon-nobita-no-shin-kyoryu-film-rescheduled-for-august-7-stand-by-me-doraemon-2-film-delayed/.157673 |website=[[Anime News Network]] |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319112622/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-03-19/doraemon-nobita-no-shin-kyoryu-film-rescheduled-for-august-7-stand-by-me-doraemon-2-film-delayed/.157673 |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"VarietySony\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/morbius-ghostbusters-afterlife-uncharted-pushed-back-2021-sony-1203549616/|title='Morbius,' 'Ghostbusters' Sequel and More Sony Movies Pushed Back to 2021|last=McNary|first=Alex Stedman,Dave|last2=Stedman|first2=Alex|date=2020-03-31|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31|last3=McNary|first3=Dave|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331105559/https://variety.com/2020/film/news/morbius-ghostbusters-afterlife-uncharted-pushed-back-2021-sony-1203549616/|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"HWRMulan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mulan-release-pushed-back-coronavirus-pandemic-1284275|title='Mulan' Release Pushed Back Amid Coronavirus Pandemic|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313171645/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mulan-release-pushed-back-coronavirus-pandemic-1284275|archive-date=March 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Cinemas in 2020}}\n*BBC ''[[Talking Movies]]'', [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/entertainment-arts-51836542/coronavirus-puts-film-industry-in-turmoil Coronavirus puts film industry in 'turmoil'], March 12, 2020\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Impact of the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\n[[Category:2020 in film]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema| ]]\n", "name_user": "Draco9904", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDelayed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impact_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic_on_cinema"}
{"title_page": "John Crowley (1659\u20131728)", "text_new": "'''John Crowley''' (3 November 1689\u20131728) of [[Barking, Suffolk]], was a British politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] from 1722 to 1728.\n\nCrowley was the son of [[Ambrose Crowley|Sir Ambrose Crowley]], MP and his wife Mary Owen, daughter of Charles Owen of London. He succeeded his father in 1713 and inherited the Crowley Iron Works in Durham, probably the biggest in the country. He married by a settlement dated 7 December 1715, Theodosia Gascoyne, daughter of Rev. Joseph Gascoyne of Enfield, Middlesex and Barking, Suffolk. One of his sisters married [[Humphrey Parsons]], another [[Sir John Hynde Cotton, 3rd Baronet]]. In September 1715 he was arrested on suspicion of being an active Jacobite, but he was soon released. During the Gyllenborg plot in 1716 and 1717, he was said to have offered \u00a320,000 for the Pretender's service. <ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url =http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/crowley-john-1689-1728 | title=CROWLEY, John (1689-1728), of Barking, Suff. | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 10 March 2019 }}</ref>   \n\nCrowley was a Freeman of the [[Worshipful Company of Drapers|Draper's  Company]], and was a Common Councillor for. Dowgate, London from 1721 to 1727.<ref name=ALD1>{{cite web |url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/no-series/london-aldermen/hen3-1912/pp119-140  |title= , 'Chronological list of aldermen: 1701-1800', in The Aldermen of the City of London Temp. Henry III - 1912 (London, 1908), pp. 119-140 | author= Alfred P Beaven |publisher= British History Online| accessdate = 10 March 2019}}</ref> He was regarded as one of the London Jacobites, and was returned as  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Okehampton (UK Parliament constituency)|Okehampton]] at the [[1722 British general election]]. He spoke against a motion for increasing the army on 26 October 1722.<ref name=HOP/> In 1723 he stood unsuccessfully for Alderman for Billingsgate.<ref name=ALD1/>. At the [[1727 British general election|1727]] he was returned as MP for [[Queenborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Queenborough]]<ref name=HOP/> but was unsuccessful in a contest at [[Ipswich (UK Parliament constituency)|Ipswich]].  He was elected Alderman for Dowgate on 28 September 1727.<ref name=ALD1/>  \n \nCrowley  died on 2 January 1728, leaving \u00a370,000 to be divided between his children comprising two sons and four daughters.   His daughter Elizabeth married [[John Ashburnham, 2nd Earl of Ashburnham]].<ref name=HOP/>\n \n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[William Northmore]]\n | before2 = [[Christopher Harris (MP)|Christopher Harris]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Okehampton (UK Parliament constituency)|Okehampton]]\n | years =   [[1722 British general election|1722]]\u2013[[1727 British general election|1727]]\n | with  =  [[Robert Pitt]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[William Northmore]]\n | after2 = [[Thomas Pitt of Boconnoc|Thomas Pitt]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[George Forbes, 3rd Earl of Granard|Captain Lord Forbes]]\n | before2 = [[John Cope (British Army officer)|Lieutenant Colonel John Cope]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Queenborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Queenborough]]\n | years =   [[1727 British general election|1727]]\u2013 1728    \n | with  =  [[Sprig Manesty]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sprig Manesty]]\n | after2 = [[George Saunders (naval officer)|Captain Sir George Saunders]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n \n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crowley, John }}\n[[Category:1689 births]]\n[[Category:1728 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n [[Category:British MPs 1722\u20131727]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n", "text_old": "'''John Crowley''' (3 November 1689\u20131728) of [[Barking, Suffolk]], was a British politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] from 1722 to 1728.\n\nCrowley was the son of [[Ambrose Crowley|Sir Ambrose Crowley]], MP and his wife Mary Owen, daughter of Charles Owen of London. He succeeded his father in 1713 and inherited the Crowley Iron Works in Durham, probably the biggest in the country. He married by a settlement dated 7 December 1715, Theodosia Gascoyne, daughter of Rev. Joseph Gascoyne of Enfield, Middlesex and Barking, Suffolk. One of his sisters married [[Humphrey Parsons]], another [[Sir John Hynde Cotton, 3rd Baronet]]. In September 1715 he was arrested on suspicion of being an active Jacobite, but he was soon released. During the Gyllenborg plot in 1716 and 1717, he was said to have offered \u00a320,000 for the Pretender\u2019s service. <ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url =http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/crowley-john-1689-1728 | title=CROWLEY, John (1689-1728), of Barking, Suff. | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 10 March 2019 }}</ref>   \n\nCrowley was a Freeman of the [[Worshipful Company of Drapers|Draper\u2019s  Company]], and was a Common Councillor for. Dowgate, London from 1721 to 1727.<ref name=ALD1>{{cite web |url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/no-series/london-aldermen/hen3-1912/pp119-140  |title= , 'Chronological list of aldermen: 1701-1800', in The Aldermen of the City of London Temp. Henry III - 1912 (London, 1908), pp. 119-140 | author= Alfred P Beaven |publisher= British History Online| accessdate = 10 March 2019}}</ref> He was regarded as one of the London Jacobites, and was returned as  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Okehampton (UK Parliament constituency)|Okehampton]] at the [[1722 British general election]]. He spoke against a motion for increasing the army on 26 October 1722.<ref name=HOP/> In 1723 he stood unsuccessfully for Alderman for Billingsgate.<ref name=ALD1/>. At the [[1727 British general election|1727]] he was returned as MP for [[Queenborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Queenborough]]<ref name=HOP/> but was unsuccessful in a contest at [[Ipswich (UK Parliament constituency)|Ipswich]].  He was elected Alderman for Dowgate on 28 September 1727.<ref name=ALD1/>  \n \nCrowley  died on 2 January 1728, leaving \u00a370,000 to be divided between his children comprising two sons and four daughters.   His daughter Elizabeth married [[John Ashburnham, 2nd Earl of Ashburnham]].<ref name=HOP/>\n \n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[William Northmore]]\n | before2 = [[Christopher Harris (MP)|Christopher Harris]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Okehampton (UK Parliament constituency)|Okehampton]]\n | years =   [[1722 British general election|1722]]\u2013[[1727 British general election|1727]]\n | with  =  [[Robert Pitt]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[William Northmore]]\n | after2 = [[Thomas Pitt of Boconnoc|Thomas Pitt]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[George Forbes, 3rd Earl of Granard|Captain Lord Forbes]]\n | before2 = [[John Cope (British Army officer)|Lieutenant Colonel John Cope]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Queenborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Queenborough]]\n | years =   [[1727 British general election|1727]]\u2013 1728    \n | with  =  [[Sprig Manesty]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sprig Manesty]]\n | after2 = [[George Saunders (naval officer)|Captain Sir George Saunders]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n \n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crowley, John }}\n[[Category:1689 births]]\n[[Category:1728 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n [[Category:British MPs 1722\u20131727]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Crowley_(1659%E2%80%931728)"}
{"title_page": "Richard Croftes", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n'''Richard Croftes''' (c. 1740 \u2013 1783) was a British politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] between 1767 and 1780.\n\n[[File:Richard Croftes of West Harling, Norfolk.jpg|thumb|Richard Croftes by Joshua Reynolds]]\nCroftes was the eldest son of William Croftes of [[West Harling]] Norfolk and [[Little Saxham]] Suffolk<ref name=CU>{{acad|id= CRFS758R|name=Crofts or Croftes, Richard}}</ref> and his wife Mary Decker, daughter of [[Sir Matthew Decker, 1st Baronet]] MP and a London merchant.<ref name=GM>{{cite book|title=The Gentleman's Magazine|date=1844|publisher=W. Pickering|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mydIAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA153|page=153|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> He was educated at [[Eton College]] from 1753 to 1758, was admitted at [[St John's College, Cambridge]]. on 3 July 1758, and graduated MA (Litt) in 1761.<ref name=CU/>\n\nIn 1760 Croftes's parents began trying to arrange a seat for him in Parliament. He was on the [[Thomas Pelham-Holles, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Duke of Newcastle]]\u2019s \"list of persons to be brought into Parliament\" on 9 June 1760, having been mentioned to him by the [[Duke of Grafton]], at the request of Mr Croftes, and by Mr Page at the request of Mrs Croftes. William Croftes was willing to pay for a seat but, found Newcastle's suggestion of Sudbury unattractive because \"it would be expensive and the success doubtful\". Mrs Croftes wrote to Newcastle on 15 February 1761 that her husband \"was willing to have parted with a large sum of money\" to have his son returned, and she herself was greatly disappointed that nothing had been arranged: \u201cWhat objections can your Grace have to serve my son? he is a worthy young man of great application, of good family, and likely to have a good fortune; I flatter myself my son\u2019s behaviour will be such that you will not repent ... bringing him into Parliament.\u201d So in Newcastle's list of people to be brought in, he then appeared as \u201cMr. Croftes, somewhere with great expense\u201d. Croftes's father asked on 9 March 1761 that he should be brought in for Newark, but this was turned down.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/croftes-richard-1740-83| title= CROFTES, Richard (c.1740\u201383), of Saxham, Suff.| publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 4 October 2017}}</ref><ref name = HOP/>\n\nIt was not until 1767 that a seat was found for Croftes on Grafton's recommendation. He was returned unopposed as a member of parliament for [[Petersfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Petersfield]] in a by-election on 17 December 1767. At the [[1768 British general election|1768 general election]] he transferred to [[Downton (UK Parliament constituency)|Downton]], where he was again returned unopposed. His father died in 1770, and Croftes succeeded to his estates.\n\nIn 1771, Grafton, now [[Chancellor of Cambridge University]], suggested that Croftes stand for one of the [[Cambridge University (UK Parliament constituency)|Cambridge University seats]], but the nomination was not well received in the University. The Bishop of Lincoln wrote to Lord Hardwicke on 5 February 1771 \"sending down so young a man, and so little known, has given much offence\". Richard Watson, regius professor of divinity, wrote to Grafton that the university was dissatisfied with Croftes. \"We have no particular objections to him as a private man; nay we believe him equal to transacting the business of Downton, but we by no means think him of consequence enough in life to be the representative, or of ability sufficient to support the interest, of the University of Cambridge\". Nevertheless, in January 1771 Croftes vacated his seat at Downton to stand for the University in a by-election on 4 February 1771. Although an independent section of the university put up their own candidate, Croftes was returned by 76 votes against 45.\n\nIn the [[1774 British general election|1774 general election]], he held one of the Cambridge University seats unopposed. However, he was defeated at the [[1780 British general election|1780 general election]] and did not stand for Parliament again. There is no record of his having spoken in the House of Commons.<ref name = HOP/>\n\nCroftes died aged 43 on 4 July 1783 and was buried at West Harling.<ref name = GM/> He had married Harriet Darell, daughter of John Darell on 11 February 1773. They had one daughter.\n\n==See also==\n\n*[http://artsalesindex.artinfo.com/auctions/Joshua-Reynolds-6619283/Portrait-of-Richard-Crofts-Of-West-Harling,-Norfolk-(Circa-1740-1783)-  Portrait of Richard Crofts Of West Harling, Norfolk by Sir Joshua Reynolds]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[John Jolliffe (of Petersfield)|John Jolliffe]]\n | before2 = [[Richard Pennant, 1st Baron Penrhyn|Richard Pennant]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = Member of Parliament for [[Petersfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Petersfield]]\n | years = 1767 \u2013 [[1768 British general election|1768]]\n | with  =  [[John Jolliffe (of Petersfield)|John Jolliffe]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[William Jolliffe (1745\u20131802)|William Jolliffe]]\n | after2 = [[Welbore Ellis, 1st Baron Mendip|Welbore Ellis]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Sir Thomas Hales, 4th Baronet|Thomas Pym Hales]]\n | before2 = [[James Hayes (1715-1800)|James Hayes]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = Member of Parliament for [[Downton (UK Parliament constituency)|Downton]]\n | years = [[1768 British general election|1768]]\u20131771\n | with  =  [[Thomas Duncombe (died 1779)|Thomas Duncombe]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Thomas Duncombe (died 1779)|Thomas Duncombe]]\n | after2 = [[James Hayes (1715-1800)|James Hayes]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[William de Grey, 1st Baron Walsingham|William de Grey]]\n | before2 = [[Thomas Townshend (MP)|Thomas Townshend]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = Member of Parliament for [[Cambridge University (UK Parliament constituency)|Cambridge University]]\n | years = 1771 \u2013 [[1780 British general election|1780]]\n | with  =  [[Thomas Townshend (MP)|Thomas Townshend]]  \n| with2  =  [[Charles Manners, 4th Duke of Rutland|Charles Manners, Marquess of Granby]]\n| with3  =  [[James Mansfield]]\n\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Lord John Townshend]]\n | after2 = [[James Mansfield]]\n}}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Croftes, Richard}}\n[[Category:1740s births]]\n[[Category:1743 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1761\u20131768]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1768\u20131774]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1774\u20131780]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n'''Richard Croftes''' (c. 1740 \u2013 1783) was a British politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] between 1767 and 1780.\n\n[[File:Richard Croftes of West Harling, Norfolk.jpg|thumb|Richard Croftes by Joshua Reynolds]]\nCroftes was the eldest son of William Croftes of [[West Harling]] Norfolk and [[Little Saxham]] Suffolk<ref name=CU>{{acad|id= CRFS758R|name=Crofts or Croftes, Richard}}</ref> and his wife Mary Decker, daughter of [[Sir Matthew Decker, 1st Baronet]] MP and a London merchant.<ref name=GM>{{cite book|title=The Gentleman's Magazine|date=1844|publisher=W. Pickering|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mydIAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA153|page=153|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> He was educated at [[Eton College]] from 1753 to 1758, was admitted at [[St John's College, Cambridge]]. on 3 July 1758, and graduated MA (Litt) in 1761.<ref name=CU/>\n\nIn 1760 Croftes's parents began trying to arrange a seat for him in Parliament. He was on the [[Thomas Pelham-Holles, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Duke of Newcastle]]\u2019s \"list of persons to be brought into Parliament\" on 9 June 1760, having been mentioned to him by the [[Duke of Grafton]], at the request of Mr Croftes, and by Mr Page at the request of Mrs Croftes. William Croftes was willing to pay for a seat but, found Newcastle's suggestion of Sudbury unattractive because \"it would be expensive and the success doubtful\". Mrs Croftes wrote to Newcastle on 15 February 1761 that her husband \"was willing to have parted with a large sum of money\" to have his son returned, and she herself was greatly disappointed that nothing had been arranged: \u201cWhat objections can your Grace have to serve my son? he is a worthy young man of great application, of good family, and likely to have a good fortune; I flatter myself my son\u2019s behaviour will be such that you will not repent ... bringing him into Parliament.\u201d So in Newcastle\u2019s list of people to be brought in, he then appeared as \u201cMr. Croftes, somewhere with great expense\u201d. Croftes's father asked on 9 March 1761 that he should be brought in for Newark, but this was turned down.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/croftes-richard-1740-83| title= CROFTES, Richard (c.1740\u201383), of Saxham, Suff.| publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 4 October 2017}}</ref><ref name = HOP/>\n\nIt was not until 1767 that a seat was found for Croftes on Grafton's recommendation. He was returned unopposed as a member of parliament for [[Petersfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Petersfield]] in a by-election on 17 December 1767. At the [[1768 British general election|1768 general election]] he transferred to [[Downton (UK Parliament constituency)|Downton]], where he was again returned unopposed. His father died in 1770, and Croftes succeeded to his estates.\n\nIn 1771, Grafton, now [[Chancellor of Cambridge University]], suggested that Croftes stand for one of the [[Cambridge University (UK Parliament constituency)|Cambridge University seats]], but the nomination was not well received in the University. The Bishop of Lincoln wrote to Lord Hardwicke on 5 February 1771 \"sending down so young a man, and so little known, has given much offence\". Richard Watson, regius professor of divinity, wrote to Grafton that the university was dissatisfied with Croftes. \"We have no particular objections to him as a private man; nay we believe him equal to transacting the business of Downton, but we by no means think him of consequence enough in life to be the representative, or of ability sufficient to support the interest, of the University of Cambridge\". Nevertheless, in January 1771 Croftes vacated his seat at Downton to stand for the University in a by-election on 4 February 1771. Although an independent section of the university put up their own candidate, Croftes was returned by 76 votes against 45.\n\nIn the [[1774 British general election|1774 general election]], he held one of the Cambridge University seats unopposed. However, he was defeated at the [[1780 British general election|1780 general election]] and did not stand for Parliament again. There is no record of his having spoken in the House of Commons.<ref name = HOP/>\n\nCroftes died aged 43 on 4 July 1783 and was buried at West Harling.<ref name = GM/> He had married Harriet Darell, daughter of John Darell on 11 February 1773. They had one daughter.\n\n==See also==\n\n*[http://artsalesindex.artinfo.com/auctions/Joshua-Reynolds-6619283/Portrait-of-Richard-Crofts-Of-West-Harling,-Norfolk-(Circa-1740-1783)-  Portrait of Richard Crofts Of West Harling, Norfolk by Sir Joshua Reynolds]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[John Jolliffe (of Petersfield)|John Jolliffe]]\n | before2 = [[Richard Pennant, 1st Baron Penrhyn|Richard Pennant]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = Member of Parliament for [[Petersfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Petersfield]]\n | years = 1767 \u2013 [[1768 Brit